Castor, -oris‚ m. : Castor and Polydeuces (Pollux), twin-brothers of Helen, were born from the second of the two eggs which Leda produced. They were believed to be the sons of Tyndareus, and are hence called Tyndaridae, and sometimes Castores—the two Castors (IV. v. 35). They were worshipped in Greece and Rome alike, and were supposed to have aided the Romans to win the battle of Lake Regillus, 496 B.C.
